. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[1124,1364,302,328]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis box="[1124,1364,302,328]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Erycibe sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from 
<specimenCount box="[278,430,338,365]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
collected from Sangihe Island and there is no additional information to assess the population size. Although the island has a rugged topography because of its volcanic origin, it had been deforested by the 1920s and now only isolated fragmentary patches of natural forest remain—it is now dominated by mixed plantations, including coconut, nutmeg, clove, sago and banana (
<bibRefCitation author="Riley, J. &amp; Wardill, J. C." box="[743,999,446,472]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="45 - 55" refId="ref6307" refString="Riley, J. &amp; Wardill, J. C. (2001) The rediscovery of Cerulean Paradise-flycatcher Eutrichomyias rowleyi on Sangihe, Indonesia. Forktail 17: 45 - 55. [https: // static 1. squarespace. com / static / 5 c 1 a 9 e 03 f 407 b 482 a 158 da 87 / t / 5 c 1 fca 7 c 40 ec 9 abd 16 b 98 e 83 / 1545587324757 / Riley-Cerulean. pdf]" type="journal article" year="2001">Riley &amp; Wardill 2001</bibRefCitation>
). The specimen was collected from the slopes of Mt Sahendaruman—the region with the most extensive remaining forest areas on Sangihe (
<bibRefCitation author="Riley, J." box="[1267,1393,482,508]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="3 - 36" refId="ref6263" refString="Riley, J. (1997) The birds of Sangihe and Talaud, North Sulawesi. Kukila 9: 3 - 36. [http: // kukila. org / index. php / KKL / article / view / 189]" type="journal article" year="1997">Riley 1997</bibRefCitation>
) but, as recorded on the label, the forest edges are threatened by agriculture. The island is still extremely poorly known and further collections and/or observations on the plant communities of the island are required to better understand the conservation status of the island’s flora and of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[659,833,590,616]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis box="[659,833,590,616]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="106" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,158,1517]" box="[189,1165,626,653]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,356,626,652]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Etymology:—</emphasis>
The specific epithet refers to Sangihe Island where this species is found.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,158,1517]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,294,662,688]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Notes:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[294,528,662,688]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis box="[294,528,662,688]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Erycibe sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique in the genus in the combination of its climbing habit, the dense indumentum throughout and the many-flowered inflorescences. This species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Merr." authorityName="Merr." box="[1052,1286,698,725]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hainanensis">
<emphasis box="[1052,1217,698,724]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. hainanensis</emphasis>
Merr.
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Merrill, E. D." pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="337 - 355" refId="ref6117" refString="Merrill, E. D. (1922) Diagnoses of Hainan plants. Philippine Journal of Science. Section C, botany 21: 337 - 355. [https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 692237]" type="journal article" year="1922">Merrill 1922: 353</bibRefCitation>
), known from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[455,522,734,760]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">China</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[579,677,734,760]" name="Vietnam" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
, in the branches and abaxial leaf surface being densely brown-hairy but differs in having 2–3(–5) subequally or unequally branched hairs, while 
<taxonomicName box="[1001,1168,770,796]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hainanensis">
<emphasis box="[1001,1168,770,796]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. hainanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has extremely unequally 2-branched hairs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,158,1517]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
Using the Flora Malesiana account of 
<bibRefCitation author="Hoogland, R. D." box="[613,818,842,869]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="404 - 431" refId="ref5890" refString="Hoogland, R. D. (1953 c) Erycibe. In: Van Steenis, C. G. G. J. (Ed.) [Convolvulaceae]. Flora Malesiana Ser. I, 4: 404 - 431." type="journal article" year="1953">Hoogland (1953c)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[830,1066,842,868]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis box="[830,1066,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Erycibe sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
would key out to 
<taxonomicName authority="Prain (1896: 536)" authorityName="Prain" authorityPageNumber="536" authorityYear="1896" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="strigosa">
<emphasis box="[1265,1386,843,868]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. strigosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Prain, D." pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="536 - 538" refId="ref6160" refString="Prain, D. (1896) Noviciae Indicae XIII. Further notes on Indian Convolvulaceae with descriptions of three additional species. Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal. Part 2, Natural History 65: 536 - 538. [https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 37193893]" type="journal article" year="1896">Prain (1896: 536)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Hoogland (1953 a: 318)" authorityName="Hoogland" authorityPageNumber="318" authorityYear="1953" box="[328,756,878,905]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subsericea">
<emphasis box="[328,481,878,904]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. subsericea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hoogland, R. D." box="[490,756,878,905]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="310 - 319" refId="ref5831" refString="Hoogland, R. D. (1953 a) Florae Malesianae Precursores II. The Convolvulaceae of Malaysia IX. Blumea 7 (2): 310 - 319." type="journal article" year="1953">Hoogland (1953a: 318)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
based on the acuminate anthers, sepals hairy on the outside, many-flowered inflorescences and hairy abaxial surface of the lamina. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prain" authorityYear="1896" box="[966,1154,914,940]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="strigosa">
<emphasis box="[966,1154,914,940]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Erycibe strigosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to Peninsular 
<collectingCountry box="[136,239,950,976]" name="Malaysia" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
but has sparsely hairy (‘strigose’) leaves and axillary inforescences, whilst 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoogland" authorityYear="1953" box="[1129,1284,950,976]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subsericea">
<emphasis box="[1129,1284,950,976]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. subsericea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to Borneo and has short-sericeous hairs on the abaxial surface of the lamina and a densely hairy (‘strigose’) ovary.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,158,1517]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
The Sangihe Islands are biogeographically close to northern Sulawesi and the 
<collectingCountry box="[1086,1216,1022,1048]" name="Philippines" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Philippines</collectingCountry>
. The only species of 
<taxonomicName box="[136,223,1058,1084]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[136,223,1058,1084]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Erycibe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
recorded from Sulawesi is 
<taxonomicName authority="C. B. Clarke (1883: 182)" authorityName="C. B. Clarke" authorityPageNumber="182" authorityYear="1883" box="[539,987,1058,1084]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="malaccensis">
<emphasis box="[539,708,1058,1084]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. malaccensis</emphasis>
C.B. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clarke, C. B." box="[761,987,1058,1084]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="179 - 228" refId="ref5433" refString="Clarke, C. B. (1883) Convolvulaceae. In: Hooker, J. D. (Ed.) Flora of British India, volume 4. L. Reeve &amp; Co Ltd., London, pp. 179 - 228. [https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 388712]" type="book chapter" year="1883">Clarke (1883: 182)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, with a disjunct distribution between the Malay Peninsula and the 
<collectingCountry box="[421,547,1094,1120]" name="Philippines" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Philippines</collectingCountry>
and Sulawesi (and perhaps Java), but absent from Sumatra and Borneo. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. B. Clarke" authorityYear="1883" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="malaccensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Erycibe malaccensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[426,602,1130,1156]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis box="[426,602,1130,1156]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in several characters especially the leaves which are soon glabrescent, the relatively smaller laminas 5–16 × 
<quantity box="[531,659,1166,1193]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="6.5" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" unit="cm" value="4.5" valueMax="6.5" valueMin="2.5">2.5–6.5 cm</quantity>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[678,854,1166,1192]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis box="[678,854,1166,1192]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
12–17 × 
<quantity box="[969,1100,1166,1193]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" metricValueMax="7.5" metricValueMin="5.5" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" unit="cm" value="6.5" valueMax="7.5" valueMin="5.5">5.5–7.5 cm</quantity>
), the fewer 4–6(–7) secondary veins (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[210,383,1202,1228]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis box="[210,383,1202,1228]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
7–10 secondary veins), the inflorescences with up to c. 20 flowers at maximum (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[1278,1451,1202,1228]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis box="[1278,1451,1202,1228]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with up to c. 100 flowers), and the hairs with a distinctly longer central branch (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[1052,1227,1238,1264]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis box="[1052,1227,1238,1264]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
hairs subequally or unequally branched). The only species in the 
<collectingCountry box="[640,766,1274,1300]" name="Philippines" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Philippines</collectingCountry>
with leaves that can be hairy abaxially are 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. B. Clarke" authorityYear="1883" box="[1245,1412,1274,1300]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="malaccensis">
<emphasis box="[1245,1412,1274,1300]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. malaccensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as previously discussed), 
<taxonomicName authority="Hoogland (1953 a: 317)" authorityName="Hoogland" authorityPageNumber="317" authorityYear="1953" box="[392,771,1310,1337]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericea">
<emphasis box="[392,504,1311,1336]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sericea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hoogland, R. D." box="[510,771,1310,1337]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="310 - 319" refId="ref5831" refString="Hoogland, R. D. (1953 a) Florae Malesianae Precursores II. The Convolvulaceae of Malaysia IX. Blumea 7 (2): 310 - 319." type="journal article" year="1953">Hoogland (1953a: 317)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Blume (1826: 1048)" authorityName="Blume (1826:" authorityPageNumber="1048" authorityYear="1048" box="[826,1208,1310,1336]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tomentosa">
<emphasis box="[826,971,1311,1336]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. tomentosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Blume, C. L." box="[978,1208,1310,1336]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" refId="ref5389" refString="Blume, C. L. (1826) Bijdragen tot de flora van Nederlandsch Indie, part 16. Batavia, Lands Drukkerij, iii + 123 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 6656" type="book" year="1826">Blume (1826: 1048)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. The laminas of all of these species are soon glabrescent abaxially but, in addition, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoogland" authorityYear="1953" box="[824,937,1347,1372]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericea">
<emphasis box="[824,937,1347,1372]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sericea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a densely hairy ovary, and the hairs of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blume (1826:" authorityYear="1048" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tomentosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. tomentosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are up to 
<quantity box="[363,449,1382,1409]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,158,1517]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Field notes record that the flower buds are dull green, and the stem and leaves are ‘with brown furry indument’. The leaves have substantial and prominent insect damage with numerous sub-spherical to elliptic holes and leaf-miner damage (omitted from the line drawing to show venation more clearly).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
